natural problem: In triangle $PQR$, point $T$ is on $PR$ and point $S$ is on $PQ$ such that $TS \parallel RQ$. The measure of $\angle RPQ$ is $65^{\circ}$, and the measure of $\angle TSQ$ is $145^{\circ}$. What is the measure of $\angle PRQ$?
natural solution: [asy] pair P,Q,R,SS,T; Q = (0,0); R = (1,0); P = (0.8,0.5); SS = 0.6*P; T = R + 0.6*(P-R); draw(T--SS--P--R--Q--SS); label("$P$",P,N); label("$S$",SS,NW); label("$Q$",Q,S); label("$R$",R,S); label("$T$",T,ENE);

[/asy] If the measure of $\angle TSQ$ is $145^{\circ}$, then the measure of $\angle TSP$ is $180^\circ - 145^\circ = 35^{\circ}$ since they are supplementary angles. The measure of $\angle RQP$ is also $35^{\circ}$ since sides $TS$ and $RQ$ are parallel.
Now we have two of the three angles in triangle $PQR$.
To find the third, we calculate $180^{\circ} - 65^{\circ} - 35^{\circ} = 80^{\circ}$. The measure of $\angle PRQ$ is $\boxed{80^{\circ}}$.
